{
	# Patron archetype briefing templates — what the company's contract
	# COMMS OFFICER reports back about their meeting with the patron's
	# representative. The player never reads a patron directly; the officer
	# is the narrator, and the archetype manifests through what they
	# observed about the patron, not the patron's own words.
	#
	# Reference character: Castle from MechWarrior Mercenaries. Pragmatic,
	# observant, dry. Reports what they saw with light editorial. Notices
	# the rep's clothing, posture, what they wouldn't explain. See
	# [[project-comms-officer-narrator]] in memory for the full design.
	#
	# Schema:
	#   {
	#     "templates": {
	#       "<ARCHETYPE_NAME>": [ "variant 1", "variant 2", ... ]
	#     }
	#   }
	#
	# - Every PatronArchetype enum value MUST appear as a key.
	# - Each archetype MUST have at least one variant string.
	# - Variants are picked deterministically per (contractId, archetype)
	#   — adding/removing/reordering variants is fine, just be aware the
	#   variant a player sees for a given contract may shift if pool size
	#   changes.
	#
	# Substitution tokens (see PatronBriefingFlavor):
	#   {patron}   — patron house display name
	#   {target}   — target planet name
	#   {payout}   — formatted payout including cash multiplier
	#   {salvage}  — negotiated salvage % (0..baseline)
	#
	# Authoring voice notes per archetype — keep the officer's tone
	# consistent; vary what they observed about the patron:
	#   TIME_RUSHED   — rep was rushed, sweaty, wouldn't explain timeline
	#   FALLEN_NOBLE  — formal-but-faded envoy, references to past status
	#                   that trail off, gentlemanly in a way that hurts
	#   TRUE_BELIEVER — long preamble about righteousness before numbers
	#                   came up; thanked us before we'd agreed
	#   ESTABLISHED   — quiet meeting, senior counsel, no specifics
	#                   spoken aloud, "we did not press"
	#   SUSPICIOUS    — walk-in, no real name, met off-site, no paperwork
	#                   beyond the contract itself
	#   NEWCOMER      — lawyer with a binder, "service deliverables,"
	#                   references requested, kickoff calls

	"templates": {
		"TIME_RUSHED": [
			"{patron}'s rep was sweating when he came in. They want {target} hit, fast — wouldn't tell me why the window's so tight. Pay's {payout}, salvage at {salvage}%. Pushed back on the timeline; didn't get an inch.",
			"{patron}'s brief came over priority comms — that costs them, and they know it. Target's {target}, {payout} on confirm. Their rep didn't sit down. Mark it urgent.",
			"Thirty-second pitch from {patron}'s people. {target}, {payout}, salvage at {salvage}%. The rep's exact words: 'We need this done before we can tell you why.' Make of that what you will."
		],

		"FALLEN_NOBLE": [
			"{patron}'s envoy came in person — that doesn't happen much anymore. Brief is {target}, terms {payout} and {salvage}% salvage. He talked about how {patron} used to handle these matters in-house, before — well. He didn't finish the sentence.",
			"Met {patron}'s rep at their consulate annex. The annex is one room now. Contract's straightforward: {target}, {payout}, salvage standard. He was a gentleman about it. I think he meant to be.",
			"Long meeting with {patron}'s people. A lot of context about why this matters to the family. The mission itself is small: {target}, salvage at {salvage}%. They want it done right. They don't have many other levers left."
		],

		"TRUE_BELIEVER": [
			"{patron}'s rep didn't want to talk numbers. Spent twenty minutes on what {target} is doing wrong. Eventually we got to {payout}, and he asked if we'd take less. I said no. Salvage at {salvage}%.",
			"Got a sermon, then a contract. {patron} wants {target} ended, full stop — the word 'ended' more than once. Pay's {payout}. The rep called the salvage 'whatever the righteous take from the unrighteous.' That parses to {salvage}%, I checked.",
			"{patron}'s envoy was the patron themselves — surprised me. They wanted to look us in the eye. {target}, {payout}, {salvage}% salvage. They thanked us before we'd agreed."
		],

		"ESTABLISHED": [
			"{patron}'s counsel came over for a working lunch. The brief is enclosed; short version is {target}, {payout} on confirmation, salvage capped at {salvage}%. They prefer not to discuss specifics aloud. The memorandum covers what we need.",
			"Quiet meeting with {patron}'s representatives. Target is {target}, payment {payout}, recovery cap {salvage}%. They were polite. They were clear. They did not elaborate, and I did not press.",
			"{patron} sent a senior partner — they don't usually. {target}, {payout}, salvage standard. He referred to the matter as 'a question of timing more than substance.' I'm choosing to take that at face value."
		],

		"SUSPICIOUS": [
			"Walk-in. {patron}, {target}, {payout} cash, {salvage}% on whatever you find. No paperwork beyond the contract itself. I asked once and dropped it. Their call.",
			"{patron}'s rep wouldn't give a real name. The brief is one page: {target}, {payout}, salvage at {salvage}%. He said they'd know if we talked about it. I believe him.",
			"Met off-site. {patron} wants {target} handled and nobody filing a report after. Pay's {payout} — the high end of what we usually see for this kind of work. Read into that what you want."
		],

		"NEWCOMER": [
			"{patron} sent a lawyer who'd clearly never bought a marine op before. He had a binder. He used the words 'service deliverables' twice. The actual contract is {target}, {payout}, {salvage}% salvage — pretty standard once we got there.",
			"First-time client. {patron}'s rep walked me through the brief like I hadn't read it. {target}, {payout} on completion, salvage at {salvage}%. They want to do this by the book. They have their own idea of what the book is.",
			"{patron}'s people are new to this and it shows. They asked for references. I gave them references. The job's {target}, terms {payout} and {salvage}% salvage, and they want a kickoff call before we mobilize — which, sure, fine."
		]
	}
}
